  <static seed="18" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/Factoring/factoring30.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the greatest common factor of the following terms.</p>
<p><m>{3x^{17}y^{6}}</m>, <m>{-9x^{16}y^{18}}</m>, <m>{27x^{6}y^{20}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>3x^{6}y^{6}\hbox{ or }-3x^{6}y^{6}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>There are three things to look for in this problem:
<ul label="disc">
<li>
<p>the greatest common <em>numerical</em> factor is <m>3</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the greatest common power of <m>x</m> is <m>x^{6}</m>, since it has the <em>lowest</em> exponent.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the greatest common power of <m>y</m> is <m>y^{6}</m>, since it has the <em>lowest</em> exponent.</p>
</li>
</ul></p>
<p>The greatest common factor of the three terms is <m>{3x^{6}y^{6}\hbox{ or }-3x^{6}y^{6}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
